                My great-grea<wbr/>&shy;t grandfathe<wbr/>&shy;r was brought to Texas as a former slave working cattle with his bosses(for<wbr/>&shy;mer slaveowner<wbr/>&shy;s) because he could make the barbecue(&quot;<wbr/>&shy;bo bo cua&quot;). On the trail it holds up well and can take days of handling fresh meat with no fridge.The cooking process is what is unchanged.<wbr/>&shy;A barrel pit is the same in theory as a hollowed ground pit.(Which my family only stopped using in the late 60's so as not to seem country)It<wbr/>&shy;s american because in Africa meat would be immediatel<wbr/>&shy;y prepared.(<wbr/>&shy;no need for heavy seasoning)<wbr/>&shy;.It is also american because they would not have been eating pork. We use the whole rib;membra<wbr/>&shy;ne and flank attached..<wbr/>&shy;cook over coals  and dont use sugar in the rub and we mop...for 200yrs now..The ribs u discuss are a product of the 80,s            </div>
            
